04686nam a22005535i 9780773598492DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20162016xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735984927 a10.1515/97807735984922doi  a(DE-B1597)656300  a(OCoLC)1032591115  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBX4839b.A44 2016 7aREL0330002bisacsh04a280/.409415090342231 aAkenson, Donald Harman, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDiscovering the End of Time :bIrish Evangelicals in the Age of Daniel O'Connell /cDonald Harman Akenson. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource :b17 photos, 5 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tMaps and Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tGod's Petrie Dish -- tDalyland: The Shape of a Hidden Kingdom -- tThe Fauna of Dalyland -- tJohn Nelson Darby Approaches Dalyland -- tThe Real World -- tThe Missing Years (1): 1819–1822 -- tThe Missing Years (2): 1822–1825 -- tEverything Implodes, 1825–1829 -- tInto Deep Eternity -- tEcclesiology: Rebuilding the Fallen Jerusalem -- tEschatology: Lady Powerscourt Points to the Heavens -- tThe Drawing Room Prophets, 1831–1832 -- tPowerscourt 1833: Apogee or Syncline? -- tThe End of the Irish Evangelicals' Big-House Tradition, 1834–1837 -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aApocalyptic millennialism is embraced by the most powerful strands of evangelical Christianity. The followers of these groups believe in the physical return of Jesus to Earth in the Second Coming, the affirmation of a Rapture, a millennium of peace under the rule of Jesus and his saints, and, at last, final judgment and deep eternity. In Discovering the End of Time, Donald Akenson traces the primary vector of apocalyptic millennialism to southern Ireland in the 1820s and ’30s. Surprisingly, these apocalyptic concepts – which many scholars associate with the poor, the ill-educated, and the desperate – were articulated most forcefully by a rich, well-educated coterie of Irish Protestants. Drawing a striking portrait of John Nelson Darby, the major figure in the evolution of evangelical dispensationalism, Akenson demonstrates Darby’s formative influence on ideas that later came to have a foundational impact on American evangelicalism in general and on Christian fundamentalism in particular. Careful to emphasize that recognizing the origins of apocalyptic millennialism in no way implies a judgment on the validity of its constructs, Akenson draws on a deep knowledge of early nineteenth-century history and theology to deliver a powerful history of an Irish religious elite and a major intersection in the evolution of modern Christianity. Opening the door into an Ireland that was hiding in plain sight, Discovering the End of Time tells a remarkable story, at once erudite, conversational, and humorous, and characterized by an impressive range and depth of research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aElite (Social sciences)zIrelandxHistoryy19th century. 0aEvangelicalismzIrelandxHistoryy19th century. 0aMillennialismzIrelandxHistoryy19th century. 0aProtestantszIrelandxHistoryy19th century. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311127380808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016z978311127630440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359849240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773598492423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773598492/original  a978-3-11-